{"format":"tiptap/v1","updatedAt":"2026-06-22T09:08:42.075Z","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Horizontal scaling of agent workers"},{"type":"text","text":" means running "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"many identical agent instances"},{"type":"text","text":" in parallel and distributing work across them so your swarm can handle thousands of concurrent users without degrading latency. Instead of making one agent “more powerful” (vertical scaling), you hire more “chefs” — more worker replicas — each handling independent tasks behind a load balancer and task queue."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What it is"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Horizontal scaling adds more "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"worker nodes"},{"type":"text","text":" (agent replicas) instead of one giant “supercomputer”:\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Load balancer"},{"type":"text","text":": Distributes incoming requests across workers.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Task queue"},{"type":"text","text":": Holds pending tasks (e.g., Redis, Kafka, Celery).\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Workers"},{"type":"text","text":": Stateless agent replicas that pull tasks from the queue.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Auto-scaler"},{"type":"text","text":": Automatically adds/removes workers based on queue depth or CPU."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Think of it like a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"call center"},{"type":"text","text":":\n- The "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"gateway"},{"type":"text","text":" is the receptionist.\n- The "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"message queue"},{"type":"text","text":" is the “hold music.”\n- The "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"workers"},{"type":"text","text":" are agents at their desks.\n- If too many people call, you hire more agents (auto-scaling)."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The goal is to keep "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"wait time (latency)"},{"type":"text","text":" constant as "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"volume (users)"},{"type":"text","text":" goes up."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Why it matters"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A single agent instance typically handles "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"10–50 concurrent users"},{"type":"text","text":" before latency degrades. Beyond that, you need:\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Horizontal scaling"},{"type":"text","text":" with a shared task queue.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Stateless workers"},{"type":"text","text":" that can pick up any task.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"External state storage"},{"type":"text","text":" (Redis, database) for context."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Without horizontal scaling:\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Latency spikes"},{"type":"text","text":" as more users queue up.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Errors increase"},{"type":"text","text":" as workers hit resource limits.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"You can’t grow"},{"type":"text","text":" beyond a small user base."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"At 10,000 users, you need a full production stack with load balancing, caching, and multi-model routing."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Mental model"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Think of horizontal scaling as "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"hiring more chefs instead of training one chef to cook faster"},{"type":"text","text":":\n- One chef (single agent) → slow, limited capacity.\n- Ten chefs (10 workers) → faster, handles more orders.\n- Queue → holds orders when chefs are busy.\n- Auto-scaler → hires more chefs when orders pile up."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Each chef is "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"stateless"},{"type":"text","text":" (doesn’t own the kitchen) and can work on any order. All context (recipes, ingredients) is in a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"shared pantry"},{"type":"text","text":" (Redis/database)."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"How it works"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"1. Stateless worker design"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Externalize all state"},{"type":"text","text":" from in-memory to Redis or a database:\n- Conversation history → Redis.\n- Tool call results → Database.\n- User context → Redis."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This ensures "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"any replica can pick up any task"},{"type":"text","text":". If state is in-memory, only the original worker can continue that task, limiting scaling."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Stateless worker\nimport redis\nfrom celery import Celery\n\nr = redis.Redis()\ncelery = Celery(\"agent_worker\", broker=\"redis://localhost:6379/0\")\n\n@celery.task\ndef run_agent(task_id: str, user_id: str):\n    # Load state from Redis\n    context = r.get(f\"user:{user_id}:context\")\n    result = agent.invoke(context)\n    # Save state to Redis\n    r.set(f\"user:{user_id}:context\", result)\n    return result"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"2. Task queue for long-running jobs"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Add a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"task queue"},{"type":"text","text":" (Redis, Kafka, Celery) for long-running agent jobs:\n- Orchestrator pushes tasks to queue.\n- Workers pull tasks and execute.\n- Queue handles retries, dead-letter, and priority."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This decouples request handling from execution, allowing workers to scale independently."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"3. Load balancing with sticky routing"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Use a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"load balancer"},{"type":"text","text":" (e.g., Kubernetes Service, AWS ALB) to distribute requests:\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Sticky routing"},{"type":"text","text":": Preserve prompt caching by routing related requests to the same worker.\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Round-robin"},{"type":"text","text":": Distribute independent requests evenly."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sticky routing helps with "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"prompt caching"},{"type":"text","text":" (reduces LLM costs), but round-robin maximizes throughput."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"4. Auto-scaling based on queue depth"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Configure an "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"HPA (Horizontal Pod Autoscaler)"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"KEDA ScaledObject"},{"type":"text","text":" to scale replicas:\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Metric"},{"type":"text","text":": Queue depth (e.g., "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"code"}],"text":"Redis queue length"},{"type":"text","text":").\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Rule"},{"type":"text","text":": “If queue depth > 50, scale up to 10 replicas.”\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Downscale"},{"type":"text","text":": “If queue depth < 10, scale down to 2 replicas.”"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Example (Kubernetes):"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"yaml"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# keda-scaledobject.yaml\napiVersion: keda.sh/v1alpha1\nkind:ScaledObject\nmetadata:\n  name: agent-worker-scaler\nspec:\n  scaleTargetRef:\n    name: agent-worker\n  triggers:\n    - type: redis\n      metadata:\n        address: redis://localhost:6379\n        key: agent_queue\n        threshold: \"50\""}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This scales replica count based on "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"queue depth"},{"type":"text","text":", not CPU/memory."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"5. Serverless fallback for spikes"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"sudden spikes"},{"type":"text","text":", use "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"AWS Lambda"},{"type":"text","text":" or "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Google Cloud Run"},{"type":"text","text":" to handle overflow:\n- Main workers handle baseline load.\n- Serverless handles overflow (even if it costs more per-token)."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This is a "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"cost trade-off"},{"type":"text","text":": serverless is more expensive but handles spikes without over-provisioning."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Architecture"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"A typical horizontal scaling stack:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"text"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐\n│  User Requests                                      │\n│  ↓                                                  │\n│  Load Balancer (ALB, Kubernetes Service)           │\n│  ↓                                                  │\n│  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐  ┌──────────┐         │\n│  │ Worker 1 │  │ Worker 2 │  │ Worker N │ ← Auto- │\n│  └──────────┘  └──────────┘  └──────────┘   Scale │\n│       ↓              ↓              ↓              │\n│  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────┐   │\n│  │  Task Queue (Redis, Kafka, Celery)        │   │\n│  └────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │\n│       ↓              ↓              ↓              │\n│  LLM (Claude) + Tools (Scrapers, Databases)      │\n│       ↓              ↓              ↓              │\n│  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────┐   │\n│  │  External State (Redis, Database)         │   │\n│  └────────────────────────────────────────────┘   │"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Implementation patterns"}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Kubernetes + KEDA"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"yaml"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# agent-worker-deployment.yaml\napiVersion: apps/v1\nkind: Deployment\nmetadata:\n  name: agent-worker\nspec:\n  replicas: 2\n  selector:\n    matchLabels:\n      app: agent-worker\n  template:\n    spec:\n      containers:\n        - name: worker\n          image: agent-worker:latest\n          env:\n            - name: REDIS_URL\n              value: \"redis://redis:6379\"\n# keda-scaledobject.yaml (see above)"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This deploys stateless workers and scales based on queue depth."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Celery + Redis"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"python"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# worker.py\nfrom celery import Celery\n\ncelery = Celery(\"agent_worker\", broker=\"redis://localhost:6379/0\")\n\n@celery.task\ndef run_agent(task_id: str, user_id: str):\n    context = r.get(f\"user:{user_id}:context\")\n    result = agent.invoke(context)\n    r.set(f\"user:{user_id}:context\", result)\n    return result"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Run workers:"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"bash"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"celery -A worker worker --concurrency=10"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Scale workers by adding more containers/pods."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Docker Compose for local scaling"}]},{"type":"codeBlock","attrs":{"language":"yaml"},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"# docker-compose.yml\nversion: \"3.8\"\nservices:\n  redis:\n    image: redis:latest\n  worker-1:\n    image: agent_worker:latest\n    environment:\n      - REDIS_URL=redis://redis:6379\n  worker-2:\n    image: agent_worker:latest\n    environment:\n      - REDIS_URL=redis://redis:6379\n  worker-3:\n    image: agent_worker:latest\n    environment:\n      - REDIS_URL=redis://redis:6379"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"This runs 3 workers locally for testing."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Benefits"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Handle thousands of concurrent users"},{"type":"text","text":" without degrading latency."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Elastic scaling"},{"type":"text","text":": Workers come online in seconds, process tasks, shut down when demand drops."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Fault tolerance"},{"type":"text","text":": If one worker fails, others pick up its tasks."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Cost efficiency"},{"type":"text","text":": Scale down when demand is low, avoid over-provisioning."}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Trade-offs"}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Benefits:"},{"type":"text","text":"\n- Aligns with "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"modern cloud infrastructure"},{"type":"text","text":" (containers, Kubernetes, serverless).\n- Handles "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"bursty traffic patterns"},{"type":"text","text":" (e.g., spikes at 9 AM).\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Independent scaling"},{"type":"text","text":": Workers scale independently of the API layer."}]},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Trade-offs:"},{"type":"text","text":"\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Adds architectural complexity"},{"type":"text","text":" (task queue, external state, auto-scaler).\n- Requires "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"stateless design"},{"type":"text","text":" (externalize all state).\n- "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Monitoring overhead"},{"type":"text","text":": Track queue depth, worker count, latency."}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Best practices"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Start with 10 workers"},{"type":"text","text":" if you have 5–10 concurrent users. Adjust based on performance."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Externalize all state"},{"type":"text","text":" to Redis or database."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Add a task queue"},{"type":"text","text":" for long-running jobs."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Use sticky routing"},{"type":"text","text":" to preserve prompt caching."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Set up distributed tracing"},{"type":"text","text":" to monitor every agent hop."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Scale based on queue depth"},{"type":"text","text":", not CPU/memory."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Monitor latency and error rates"},{"type":"text","text":" to know when to scale."}]}]}]},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":2},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"Key takeaways"}]},{"type":"bulletList","content":[{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Horizontal scaling = "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"running more identical worker replicas"},{"type":"text","text":" in parallel, distributing work across them."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Stateless workers"},{"type":"text","text":" are the foundation: externalize all state to Redis/database so any worker can pick up any task."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Task queue"},{"type":"text","text":" (Redis, Kafka, Celery) decouples request handling from execution."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Auto-scaling"},{"type":"text","text":" based on queue depth (e.g., KEDA, HPA) handles spikes without manual intervention."}]}]},{"type":"listItem","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Start with "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"10 workers"},{"type":"text","text":" for 5–10 concurrent users, then adjust based on latency and error rates."}]}]}]},{"type":"paragraph"}]}}
